## 4. TRANSACTION ISOLATION AND LOCKING MECHANISMS

### Advisory Locks (Host-Level)

PostgreSQL advisory locks are used to serialize dispatch operations on a single host:

**File**: `/Users/dtavares/dev/OpenCue/rust/crates/scheduler/src/dao/host_dao.rs` (lines 268-306)

```rust
pub async fn lock(
    &self,
    transaction: &mut Transaction<'_, Postgres>,
    host_id: &Uuid,
) -> Result<bool> {
    trace!("Locking {}", host_id);
    sqlx::query_scalar::<_, bool>("SELECT pg_try_advisory_lock(hashtext($1))")
        .bind(host_id.to_string())
        .fetch_one(&mut **transaction)
        .await
        .into_diagnostic()
        .wrap_err("Failed to acquire advisory lock")
}

pub async fn unlock(
    &self,
    transaction: &mut Transaction<'_, Postgres>,
    host_id: &Uuid,
) -> Result<bool> {
    trace!("Unlocking {}", host_id);
    sqlx::query_scalar::<_, bool>("SELECT pg_advisory_unlock(hashtext($1))")
        .bind(host_id.to_string())
        .fetch_one(&mut **transaction)
        .await
        .into_diagnostic()
        .wrap_err("Failed to release advisory lock")
}
```

### Transaction Enforcement in Dispatch Flow

**File**: `/Users/dtavares/dev/OpenCue/rust/crates/scheduler/src/pipeline/dispatcher/actor.rs` (lines 170-218)

```rust
async fn dispatch(
    &self,
    layer: &DispatchLayer,
    host: Host,
    transaction: &mut Transaction<'_, Postgres>,
) -> Result<(Host, DispatchLayer), DispatchError> {
    let host_id = host.id;

    // Acquire lock first
    if !self
        .host_dao
        .lock(transaction, &host.id)
        .await
        .map_err(DispatchError::Failure)?
    {
        return Err(DispatchError::HostLock(host.name.clone()));
    }

    // Ensure unlock is always called, even on panic
    let result = std::panic::AssertUnwindSafe(self.dispatch_inner(layer, host))
        .catch_unwind()
        .await;

    // Always attempt to unlock
    if let Err(unlock_err) = self.host_dao.unlock(transaction, &host_id).await {
        trace!("Failed to unlock host {}: {}", host_disp, unlock_err);
    }
```

### Frame-Level Optimistic Locking

Frames use version-based optimistic locking to detect concurrent modifications:

**File**: `/Users/dtavares/dev/OpenCue/rust/crates/scheduler/src/dao/frame_dao.rs` (lines 162-177)

```sql
static UPDATE_FRAME_STARTED: &str = r#"
UPDATE frame SET
    str_state = 'RUNNING',
    str_host = $1,
    int_cores = $2,
    int_mem_reserved = $3,
    int_gpus = $4,
    int_gpu_mem_reserved = $5,
    ts_updated = current_timestamp,
    ts_started = current_timestamp,
    ts_stopped = null,
    int_version = int_version + 1
WHERE pk_frame = $6
    AND str_state = 'WAITING'
    AND int_version = $7  -- Optimistic lock on version
"#;
```

This is checked via:

**File**: `/Users/dtavares/dev/OpenCue/rust/crates/scheduler/src/dao/frame_dao.rs` (lines 213-254)

```rust
pub async fn update_frame_started(
    &self,
    transaction: &mut Transaction<'_, Postgres>,
    virtual_proc: &VirtualProc,
) -> Result<(), FrameDaoError> {
    let result = sqlx::query(UPDATE_FRAME_STARTED)
        .bind(virtual_proc.host_name.clone())
        .bind(virtual_proc.cores_reserved.value())
        // ... bind other parameters
        .bind(virtual_proc.frame.id.to_string())
        .bind(virtual_proc.frame.version as i32)  // Version for optimistic lock
        .execute(&mut **transaction)
        .await
        .map_err(FrameDaoError::DbFailure)?;

    // Check if the update actually modified a row
    if result.rows_affected() == 0 {
        return Err(FrameDaoError::FrameCouldNotBeUpdated);
    }
```

